      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            One winter morning snow begins to fall in my rural community at a constant rate.  I wake up and get in my plow to clear my road, setting off at <m>8</m>am, and after one hour I have cleared <m>2</m> miles of road.  It takes me two more hours to clear the next two miles, as the snow keeps falling.  Assume my plow clears snow at a constant rate of volume over time, and that if <m>x(t)</m> is the distance my plow is from the start at time t, <m>x’(t) = k/t</m> for some constant <m>k</m>.  What time did it start snowing?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>k(x)=f(x)+6</m>. So, we can shift the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> up <m>6</m> units to obtain <m>y=k(x)</m>.
